<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-562-925  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 562 925.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DG Review  Oct 1990 v11 n4 p33(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Making the upgrade.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Horvitz, Phil.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>There are several options open to Data General users forupgrading.andP;  Each one receives a PH Bang-for-the-Buck (PHBB)rating.andP;  Upgrading the CPU receives a B- rating.andP;  Only if a fasterCPU is actually what the system needs should the CPU be upgraded.andO;Memory upgrading receives an A rating.andP;  Adding memory is thecheapest way to improve performance and eliminate contention ifthe system is experiencing memory contention.andP;  Disk drive upgradesreceive an A rating.andP;  Disk I/O is the most frequent performancebottleneck.andP;  Moving from a Data General MV to an AViiON is notconsidered an upgrade, but customers should evaluate the risks andcosts of remaining with a proprietary system and explore otherarchitectures.andP;  PC integration receives an A+ rating.andP;  The life ofan MV can be extended if there is a local area network with PCsand word processing and spreadsheet work is offloaded to the PCs.andO;The best solution at this time is PC-to-MV integration.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Data General Corp. (Products).andO;Product:   Data General Aviion (Workstation) (Usage).andO;Topic:     UpgradingMicrocomputersDisk DrivesMemoryPerformance Improvement.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>